This project investigated approaches to improving the performance and scalability of multi-server private information retrieval using the concept of "batching". Intuitively, batching refers to the techniques that can amortize the cost of PIR query processing by (i) encoding several queries into a single, multiblock query, (ii) encoding databases in ways that facilitate more efficient retrieval of multiple datablocks at once, (iii) processing unrelated requests in parallel in ways that reduce the server-borne cost per request, or (iv) some combination of the above.

The primary outcomes of the research include

    1) new construction allowing the flexible tradeoffs between communication cost, server-side computation cost, and Byzantine robustness in IT-PIR based on Shamir secret sharing (and related ramp schemes);

    2) a novel technique that allows single-round keyword-like (batch) retrieval in multiserver PIR schemes via a primitive called "indexes of queries";

    3) a new many-server PIR protocol that provides provably optimal download and server-side computation costs, with extremely low (albeit, not provably optimal) upload and client-side computation costs;

    4) new techniques for using secure multiparty computation to train collaborative filtering models and render collaborative filtering recommendations over compact multiserver PIR queries in the context of PIR-backed media streaming services;

    5) open-source implementations of each of the above.

Not only do these findings significantly advance the state of the art with respect to scalable and efficient multi-server PIR, but they also illuminate several promising areas for future work. For example, efforts are underway to extend the work on indexes of queries (contribution 2 above) to work with arbitrary PIR protocols and with less structured database schemas, which will significantly expand set range of use cases for which non-experts can safely employ PIR techniques; the many-sever PIR protocol (contribution 3 above) demonstrates that PIR can be significantly faster than previously believed, while raising questions around lower bounds on upload cost and the relation between upload and download cost in optimal-rate protocols; and the work on collaborative filtering (contribution 4 above) demonstrates that practically efficient PIR-based internet services could indeed be feasibly deployed. The open-source implementations make it easy for others to replicate these findings, improve on them, and incorporate them into new systems.

